More than a dozen guards from Blue House, South Korea's presidential palace, have been ordered to self-quarantine for two weeks after church and military officials reported cases of COVID-19 pneumonia. Meanwhile, South Korea reported a 100-person surge in confirmed cases on February 21st, doubling the total number of cases to 204.

A 75-year-old man living in Seoul has become the 56th confirmed case of new coronary pneumonia in South Korea, the South Korean Ministry of Disease Management reported Friday, according to the South Korean newspaper joongang daily. Investigations revealed that the patient had visited Hana ear, nose and Throat Hospital near Gyeongbokgung Station five times between February 6 and 17. The hospital is only a kilometre from Blue House, and guards from Blue House regularly visit it.

After the track of the 56th confirmed patient was made public, the Seoul Metropolitan Police Agency conducted a survey of police officers who had visited the hospital and found that more than 20 officers from the Seoul Metropolitan Police Department had visited the hospital during that period. More than a dozen of them are part of the 101st Guard Regiment, which is responsible for the internal security of Blue House, and officers from the 202nd Guard Regiment, which is responsible for the security of the Outer Blue House, also visit the hospital.

On Feb. 21, South Korean police sources said they had asked police officers who may have come into contact with the patient to rest at home for 14 days from the date of their last visit to the eye, nose and Throat Hospital.

Blue House fire brigade members were also reported to have visited the hospital on the same day as the 56th patient. The Blue House Guard Corps and the Presidential Security Service have recently completed their internal epidemic prevention work.

The police said they did not investigate whether there were any police officers in contact with members of the "new world" Church who were involved in the outbreak of the cluster infection, nor did they ask police officers to report it.

Blue House has always been free to enter the visitors to visit reservations, but a Blue House aide told Yonhap on the 21st, in view of the spread of the new crown pneumonia situation, Blue House is considering the suspension of visitors to visit inside. The last time Blue House suspended foreign visitors was in September 2009, when swine flu was raging, and it did not reopen six months later in March 2010.

The day before, South Korean President Moon jae-in and his wife Kim Jong-suk had lunch in Blue House with the creators of the oscar-winning film parasites. Director Bong Joon-ho and actors including Song Kang-ho, Lee Sun-gyun and Cao Ruzhen, as well as culture, Sports and Tourism Minister Park Liangyu, were present.

As of the afternoon of the 21st, South Korea has confirmed 204 new cases of pneumonia, of which 16 have been discharged, making it the second-largest number of confirmed cases overseas, after neighboring Japan. South Korea Central Epidemic Prevention Countermeasures Headquarters Minister Jeong eun-kyung 21 at a regular press conference, said that there are 6 to 7 confirmed patients with relatively serious condition, concentrated in Gyeongsang North Road County South Hospital. The hospital was the site of South Korea's first fatal case of new coronary pneumonia.

In addition, from January 31 to February 2, the 31st confirmed patient in South Korea attended the funeral of the chief brother of the "new world" sect at the hospital. Yonhap said there may have been a lot of "Xintiandi" believers attended the funeral.

As of 4:00 pm on the 21st, there were 48 more confirmed cases in South Korea, 46 of which were related to the new World Church in Taegu, and 42 in Daegu. Of the 156 previously confirmed cases, 98 were linked to the new world church in Taegu. That means 144 of the 204 patients diagnosed so far are church-related.

South Korea Central Epidemic Prevention Countermeasures Minister Jeong eun-kyung said the epidemic is caused by a single infection of a larger group of infections, the original source of infection is still under investigation, but it is certain that the epidemic is spreading in a certain connection. He said he had obtained a list of 1,001 members of the new World Taegu Church who had worshiped with the 31st patient on the 9th and 16th of this month and was placing them under home quarantine.

The World Health Organization (WHO) said in an e-mail response to the central daily newspaper that the outbreak of a new coronavirus mass infection in Taegu could be a "super-transmission" event.

South Korean President Moon jae-in on the 21st instructed to thoroughly investigate those attending the new World Church service in Taegu and the funeral of gyeongsang-do-do-do-jun dae-nam hospital. Prime Minister Chung Sye-kyun reported on plans to designate Daegu and North Gyeongsang Province as special control areas for infectious diseases, and said he would obtain lists of religious believers and conduct all tests under home quarantine. Moon pointed out that instead of waiting for the new heaven and Earth Church to provide the list, more rapid action should be taken.

At a press conference on the 21st, Park ling-hou, head of the South Korean Central Emergency Response Department and Minister of Health and Welfare, said that the epidemic prevention authorities believe that the current epidemic of new crown pneumonia in South Korea has not yet shown signs of spreading throughout the country, it was therefore decided to maintain the second level of "vigilance" at the early warning level, but to respond in practice at the highest "serious" level.

Park said that although the epidemic has entered the initial stage of community transmission, it has not yet reached the stage of spread throughout the country because it is a concentrated infection in a specific group and the route of infection is clear, can still be controlled through the existing epidemic prevention system. He noted that most confirmed cases with no underlying history were cured within 2-3 weeks.

Moon spoke by telephone with Chinese President Xi Jinping on the afternoon of the 20th to discuss the two countries'joint response to the outbreak of the new coronavirus. The two countries decided to share clinical treatment experience and strengthen cooperation on epidemic prevention. In addition, the two heads of state decided to push President Xi Jinping to visit South Korea in the first half of this year as originally planned.
